["Clinical documentation reviewed in PowerChart, 70-year-old male with a history of morbid obesity  COPD  A. fib PE on several toe  diabetes  hypertension  hyperlipidemia and congestive heart rate who presents emergency department for difficulty breathing and a fall. History is limited by the patient's respiratory status. He states that he slipped out of his lazy boy today could not get back up. EMS was called. He has been having worsening difficulty breathing over the last 2 weeks. He has been using his inhalers. He reports a nonproductive cough. It is unclear if he has had any fevers. He denied any chest pain. He does state that his legs have been swelling. Patient denied any prior intubations. He states he does not use a BiPAP., Patient was started on breathing treatments and placed on BiPAP. Patient's initial ABG showed an acute respiratory acidosis with a pH of 7.29  PCO2 of 67 and a PO2 of 153. His bicarbonate was 32.5 and his lactate was 0.9. His chest x-ray was concerning for patchy multifocal bilateral opacities which may represent edema or infiltrate. Patient's troponin was negative. Patient had a mild leukocytosis at 12.5. His anemia was unchanged BNP was in process. He did not have any evidence of new renal dysfunction. A d-dimer came back mildly elevated  however his chronic renal disease precludes him from getting a CT angiogram. Patient will need a VQ scan while inpatient/when stable, Despite continuous nebulizer treatments on BiPAP the patient continued to become progressively confused. His wife was able to come to the bedside and reported the patient has been progressively declining for the last 3 months. He had approximately 8 falls during this time. He had had worsening daily confusion and lethargy. Patient frequently been falling asleep even during meals or while going to the bathroom., The patient's progressive confusion was concerning for BiPAP failure and so the decision was made to intubate the patient for hypercapnic respiratory failure. Processing New Row [nil, nil, "84-year-old Caucasian gentleman with a past medical history significant for paroxysmal atrial fibrillation, not previously on anticoagulation as well as hypertension, not on home medications, who has not seen a primary care physician in sometime who presented to St. Ann's Hospital secondary to an episode of right lower extremity weakness and was found to have a left thalamic ischemic infarct. \u00A0The patient was not a candidate for TPA. \u00A0His symptoms improved. \u00A0He was seen by Cardiology as well as Neurology. \u00A0His workup included carotid duplex and echocardiogram did not show any intracardiac thrombus or shunts or critical stenosis in his carotid arteries. \u00A0He was recommended for anticoagulation with Xarelto by Cardiology, which Neurology was okay starting on discharge as the patient has a small stroke with very minimal risk for hemorrhagic conversion. He was also found to have an elevated TSH of 18.63 with no prior diagnosis of hypothyroidism as well as a free T4 of 0.7. \u00A0The patient was started on weight-based Synthroid at 137 mcg daily. \u00A0He is to follow up with his primary care physician to have his thyroid function rechecked. \u00A0He was also found to be hypertensive and does not appear to have been on any home medications. \u00A0He was started on hydrochlorothiazide 25 mg daily. \u00A0He was evaluated by Physical Therapy and Occupational Therapy and then recommended for outpatient PT and OT. \u00A0He was cleared for discharge by all consultants and was discharged in stable condition.", nil, nil]
Initial Row Type Indicator = Note Detail
Row[2] = 84-year-old Caucasian gentleman with a past medical history significant for paroxysmal atrial fibrillation, not previously on anticoagulation as well as hypertension, not on home medications, who has not seen a primary care physician in sometime who presented to St. Ann's Hospital secondary to an episode of right lower extremity weakness and was found to have a left thalamic ischemic infarct.  The patient was not a candidate for TPA.  His symptoms improved.  He was seen by Cardiology as well as Neurology.  His workup included carotid duplex and echocardiogram did not show any intracardiac thrombus or shunts or critical stenosis in his carotid arteries.  He was recommended for anticoagulation with Xarelto by Cardiology, which Neurology was okay starting on discharge as the patient has a small stroke with very minimal risk for hemorrhagic conversion. He was also found to have an elevated TSH of 18.63 with no prior diagnosis of hypothyroidism as well as a free T4 of 0.7.  The patient was started on weight-based Synthroid at 137 mcg daily.  He is to follow up with his primary care physician to have his thyroid function rechecked.  He was also found to be hypertensive and does not appear to have been on any home medications.  He was started on hydrochlorothiazide 25 mg daily.  He was evaluated by Physical Therapy and Occupational Therapy and then recommended for outpatient PT and OT.  He was cleared for discharge by all consultants and was discharged in stable condition.

Row[2] = Critical care the patient presenting with severe hypotension and possible septic shock on top of worsening lactic acidosis and concerning abdominal exam.  Given the history of mitral regurgitation, the history of atrial fibrillation, and a new splenic infarct seen, I do worry about possible embolic phenomenon to the abdomen leading to ischemic bowel.  In addition, she does have significant small-bowel obstruction as well.  Even though, she is on Eliquis, perhaps with her unable to take p.o., she is unable to absorb that medication.  I did discuss with her family, specifically her daughter and her sister, the severity of the situation and the need for urgent/emergent surgery.  I updated Surgery and the medical house officers as well.  At this point, I agree with aggressive fluid resuscitation still, judicious pressors, and even consideration for bicarbonate drip.  Continue on pressors as necessary, including vasopressin and Levophed.  I will place her on stress dose hydrocortisone as well.  Prognosis is quite guarded at best.
